John. P. Newell:  Exceptionally Large Icebergs and Ice Islands … HB 2672 Nov 20: The longest berg was met off the Baffin Land coast on Sep 14. It was in the form of a chain of flat-topped bergs that must have totalled 5 miles or more in length. The largest piece, which was separated from other smaller ones by gaps of 2 or 3 ship's lengths, measured 2.3 miles. The height which was quite unform was only 45'. Although this chain of ice islets was more than 20 miles from the nearest land, and a heavy ocean swell prevailed, 2 polar bears were sighted cantering along the top of the berg, then disappeared in toward the center, apparently frightened by the sight of the ship. IP Bulletin 1940 Vol.30: fig.12 shows a diagram of this berg and the longest side is labelled as 3.2 miles, not labelled as nm., which suggests the 2.3 miles mentioned in the text should be 3.2. Though irregularly shaped the maximum width is apparently about the same. The berg was seen by the Nascopie about a week earlier and is thought to be the same berg in about the same place as was seen by the Nascopie in the previous year]
